<header>
  <h1>Sustainability Interval Index (SII)</h1>
  <p>Conrad Challenge – Innovation Stage Project</p>
  <p>
    The Sustainability Interval Index (SII) is a novel computational framework that rethinks how
    corporate sustainability is measured. This project introduces a more transparent,
    uncertainty-aware, and actionable alternative to traditional sustainability scoring models.
  </p>
</header>

<nav>
  <a href="#about">Overview</a>
  <a href="#innovation">Innovation</a>
  <a href="#team">Team</a>
  <a href="#impact">Impact</a>
</nav>

<section id="about">
  <h2>Project Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Our goal was to address a fundamental flaw in existing sustainability ratings: the assumption that complex,
    uncertain environmental data can be accurately represented by single, exact numbers.
  </p>
  <p>
    SII replaces this assumption with an interval-based, fuzzy-logic-driven approach that produces
    a <em>range</em> of sustainability outcomes and clearly identifies the factors that matter most.
    This enables companies, investors, and policymakers to make better-informed decisions under
    uncertainty.
  </p>

  <h2>Problem & Solution</h2>
  <p>
    Traditional sustainability ratings rely on exact values and rigid assumptions, despite
    corporate environmental data often being incomplete, estimated, or subjective.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Sustainability Interval Index (SII) addresses this challenge by modeling sustainability as
    a <strong>range</strong> rather than a single number.
  </p>
</section>

<section id="innovation">
  <h2>Technical Innovation</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Interval-Based Inputs:</strong> Sustainability indicators are entered as ranges.</li>
    <li><strong>Universal Normalization:</strong> Indicators are transformed to a [0,1] scale.</li>
    <li><strong>Fuzzy Logic Evaluation:</strong> Indicators are mapped using triangular membership functions.</li>
    <li><strong>Hierarchical Modeling:</strong> Indicators feed into higher-level sustainability concepts.</li>
    <li><strong>Rule-Set Aggregation:</strong> Recursive fuzzy rules produce the final SII.</li>
    <li><strong>Interval Optimization:</strong> Best- and worst-case sustainability outcomes are identified.</li>
    <li><strong>Branch-and-Bound Optimization:</strong> Exact global results with computational efficiency.</li>
    <li><strong>Impact Sensitivity Analysis:</strong> Identifies which indicators most affect the score.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

